#: ../../S/spike.rst:5
msgid "spike"
msgstr "spike"

#: ../../S/spike.rst:7
msgid "v\\."
msgstr "動詞"

#: ../../S/spike.rst:10
msgid ""
"To defeat a selection mechanism by introducing a (sometimes temporary) "
"device that forces a specific result. The word is used in several "
"industries; telephone engineers refer to spiking a relay by inserting a pin "
"to hold the relay in either the closed or open state, and railroaders refer "
"to spiking a track switch so that it cannot be moved. In programming "
"environments it normally refers to a temporary change, usually for testing "
"purposes (as opposed to a permanent change, which would be called "
":ref:`hardwired`\\)."
msgstr ""
"(時には一時的な)装置を導入して特定の結果を強制することで、選択機構を打ち破ること。この語はいくつかの業界で使われる。電話技師は、リレーを閉じた状態か開いた状態に保つためにピンを差し込むことをspiking"
" a relayと呼び、鉄道員は、転轍機が動かせないようにすることをspiking a track "
"switchと呼ぶ。プログラミング環境では、通常、テスト目的の一時的な変更を指す(永続的な変更とは対照的で、それは\\ "
":ref:`hardwired`\\ と呼ばれるだろう)。"

#: ../../S/spike.rst:15
msgid ""
"[borderline techspeak] A visible peak in an otherwise rather constant graph "
"(e.g. a sudden surge in line voltage, an unexpected short \"high\" on a "
"logical line in a circuit). Hackers frequently use this for a sudden short "
"increase in some quantity such as system load or network traffic."
msgstr ""
"[techspeak寄り] "
"そうでなければかなり一定のグラフにおける目に見えるピーク(たとえば、線電圧の突然の急上昇、回路の論理線上の予期しない短い「ハイ」)。ハッカーは、システム負荷やネットワークトラフィックのような何らかの量の突然の短い増加に、これをよく使う。"
